(display:"Styles")


:: page 5 [en] {"position":"725,300","size":"100,100"}
The crowd was thick, and we shuffled forward in the endless line until it was finally our turn to enter.

At the gates, every staff member wore the same perfectly curved smile—polished, professional, and yet disturbingly identical, as if carved onto their faces. It was admirable in its precision, but the longer I stared, the more unnatural it felt, like mannequins programmed to mimic joy.

The attendant before us spoke in a flat, mechanical tone, each syllable rehearsed to perfection:
“Welcome to the park. We wish you a pleasant day.”

Without breaking that eerie smile, they handed us a glossy brochure. The pages were filled with cheerful colors and neatly printed rules—safety reminders, ride instructions, the usual. But as I flipped through, I couldn’t shake the feeling that something was missing, something hidden between the lines.

The words seemed ordinary, yet the atmosphere pressed down on me, whispering how the consequences of the rules were far more serious than I thought.

[[Next->page 6]]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 5.5 (optional) 可刪減 {"position":"725,425","size":"100,100"}
我拿著手冊看著地圖，遊樂設施種類除了最多人去的馬戲團，其他設施也就跟其他樂園沒有什麼差別。

我瞄了一眼右下角的沈悶的樂園守則，

守則的部分突然變成腥紅色的樣子，我揉了揉眼睛，心想著難道看錯了？

守則那部份有回復正常。

你沒事吧？

帶著疑慮前往馬戲團的場地

visual 閃爍+突然出現？


:: page 6 [en] {"position":"850,300","size":"100,100"}
We arrived at the grand entrance of the circus, waiting in line with the others. The tent loomed above us, its fabric a deep crimson that seemed almost alive under the glow of the lights. Cheerful music spilled out from within, mingling with the chatter of excited visitors, creating a lively facade that only made the unease in my chest grow stronger.

“Welcome,” a voice intoned.

Another set of rules. The brochure read:

No filming or phone calls inside the venue.

During the wait for performances, refrain from loud talking or chatter that might disturb the performers preparing backstage.

When the host requests audience reaction, spectators must respond with enthusiastic applause.

In the event of an accident, remain calm, follow our instructions, and do not attempt to leave on your own.

Violators will be dealt with by staff.

My eyes froze on that final line. Dealt with. A shiver ran down my spine before I could stop it.

Something about this place was wrong. First the terrified vagrant’s warning, now this strange atmosphere—too polished, too controlled. My suspicious nature couldn’t help but spin darker possibilities. Was I stepping into the pages of a horror novel?

Samuel noticed my unease and placed a hand on my shoulder.
“You alright? You look pale ever since we got here.”

And now the choice pressed against me like a weight:
[[Pretend everything is fine]]
[[Tell him about the strange atmosphere]]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 8 [en] {"position":"1100,300","size":"100,100"}
We slipped into our seats, the tent buzzing with anticipation.

Though the rules clearly forbade filming, I couldn’t resist. I slid my camera into a barely noticeable spot, its lens peeking out just enough. Truth be told, no one seemed to care—plenty of visitors were snapping photos, chatting loudly, breaking every rule printed in that brochure.

The lights dimmed. A sudden burst of music filled the air, and the host’s voice thundered across the stage, pulling the atmosphere taut like a drumskin.

“Ladies and gentlemen, welcome to the most spectacular show in the land…”

His words rolled with theatrical grandeur, each syllable designed to electrify the crowd.

“And now, let’s give a big round of applause to our performers today!”

The audience erupted, clapping and cheering with a feverish energy. The performers stepped forward, their smiles wide, their movements sharp, as if choreographed down to the smallest gesture.

I felt the weight of the rules again—applause when asked, silence when told. And though everyone around me seemed swept up in the excitement, a chill lingered at the back of my mind.

[[Next->page 9]]
(display:"Styles")


:: page 9 [en] {"position":"1225,300","size":"100,100"}
The show unfolded. First came the clown, dressed in vibrant colors, juggling bright balls with practiced ease. Every so often he fumbled deliberately, drawing laughter from the children whose giggles rippled through the tent.

Then the beast‑master strode in, commanding a pride of golden lions. Their coats gleamed under the spotlights, their bodies powerful and tense. At his signal they leapt through iron hoops, bounded through rings of fire, and rose on hind legs in perfect balance. The audience roared with applause, swept up in the spectacle.

For two hours the performances surged one after another, each act more extravagant than the last. The atmosphere climbed to a fever pitch, the crowd clapping and cheering until the tent itself seemed to tremble with sound.

And yet, beneath the thunderous ovation, I felt the faint echo of the rules—those strange, rigid commands—and the memory of the vagrant’s warning. As the finale approached, I couldn’t shake the thought: perhaps the true show was only just beginning.
(8 &9 match)

[[Next->page 10]]
(display:"Styles")


